				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Lookin to Twink a bard!<a name="30033"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 24 04 1:30 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I would have to agree with the posts above.  If you are gonna twink a bard, then do it lightly to begin with, and move up from there.  Dont power twink one off the bat, or you will regret it later in life.  Definately, dont pl a bard.  Do it either in legit groups, or solo for it.  But dont waste the levels you have to go through, by doing it with no chance of death.
<br />

<br />
Now that being said, a little bit of help for the lower levels is not always a bad thing.  If the truth be told, i started out as a sk, and played one till after the release of luclin.  At that point, I got bored, and minorly twinked a bard that i had created to make fun of a friend of mine who used to play(Hence the screwed up name)
<br />

<br />
I think when I started to play him seriously, I started with singing steel boots, gloves, bracer, arms, helm, iksar regen bp, and labent legs, if i remember correctly.  Somewhere around level 30, i picked up singing steel legs, and at 45, sold everything my sk had (full suit of blood ember minus bp (hey, it was just after luclin release =P) and bought a singing steel bp.  Yea, i was in full singing steel at 45.  Picked up a few weapons here and there, and hunted forever for drums of the beast at around level 50ish.
<br />

<br />
I was never powerleveled at any point, but did solo like a mad man, pushing atleast a level a day or more, and did 20 to 55 in about 5 weeks.  During this I did a lot of reading, experimentation, talked to other bards, and just learned to enjoy the bardic lifestyle.  
<br />

<br />
58 i changed my guild tag to GoTK, and spent the last year and a half exploring all of velious, luclin, and PoP.  During that first few months, i was lucky enough to be grouped with the greatest group of bards, that any guild would be lucky to count their own.  I learned more there, about bards than i had in 58 levels previously, and practiced up on a lotta things that i was rusty on.
<br />

<br />
Survie through velious content, at level 60, with a whopping 1800 hps, being MA bard with an Tank that tried his damdest to get you killed every fight =), and you tend to learn the raiding bardic life.  Then again, i am a complete belive in progression through EQ, as i think you miss things if you skip right to 65 and head to planes of power.  
<br />

<br />
All in all, i turned out okay, with a bit of help in the beginning.  Just take the time to learn each of the major things for bards, and play and experiment enough to get comfortable in all situations.  Take time out every couple levels, and practice the different aspects of a bard, and you will turn out alright.  
<br />

<br />
Dont be that idiot that sent me a tell asking quesitons the other day, the level 3 bard in a fungi asking what an instrament modifier was, and why they shoud worry about it.  Or the one two days later that was 56, and wondering if &quot;he should bother with epic, cause his friend that was a bard said it was not worth it, while wielding his happily Ebayed Edge of Eternity and Songblade of Eternal.
<br />

<br />
And one last note, there are better things to put your starting points into than splitting them between dex/cha.<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-10.gif" border="0" alt="Blushing" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span></td>
